Hello,

I am right now building some form in flutter using `TextFormField`s as described here https://flutter.dev/docs/cookbook/forms/validation.

The `validator` parameter of `TextFormField` is defined as some` typedef FormFieldValidator<T> = String Function(T value)`.
It might seem like a small thing, but this forces to return `null` for indicating a valid input. This just feels wrong and looks wrong. If anything I would assume `null` being an invalid state.

Due to using Rust language recently, I would propose something that feels a bit similiar to the Rust `Result<T1, T2>` type, which I think is a good idea (so I want more of that :). The following may not be too Dart-Idiomatic due to lack of knowledge, however I hope it still makes the point clear:

```dart
/// This can be returned on any operation which may or may not succeed
/// for any defined reason
class Result<S, E> {
  final S success;
  final E error;
  final bool isOk;

  bool get isError => !isOk;

  /// Do not use this constructor, instead ise [Result.Ok] or [Result.Error]
  Result._(this.isOk, {this.success, this.error});

  factory Result.Ok([S result]) {
    return Result._(
        true,
        success: result,
        error: null
    );
  }

  factory Result.Error([E error]) {
    return Result._(
        false,
        success: null,
        error: error
    );
  }

  /// Depending on [isOk] this will return the value of type [S] or type [E]
  dynamic unrwap() {
    if(isOk) return success;
    return error;
  }
}

/// New type for the form field validator attribute
typedef FormFieldValidator<T> = Result<void, String> Function(T);


/// some validator
FormFieldValidator<String> getValidator() {
  return (String input) {
    bool successful = input == "42";
    if(successful) {
      return Result.Ok();
    } else {
      return Result.Error("Something made boo boo");
    }
  };

}


void main() {
  var validator = getValidator();
  print("Does not validate");
  var result = validator("does not validate");
  print("Has error? ${result.isError}\nIs ok? ${result.isOk}\nResult: ${result.unrwap()}");

  print('-------');

  print("Does validate");
  result = validator("42");
  print("Has error? ${result.isError}\nIs ok? ${result.isOk}\nResult: ${result.unrwap()}");
}
```
with that the declaration of `FormFieldValidator`could be changed to `typedef FormFieldValidator<T> = Result<void, String> Function(T)`. This pattern could also be used in any similar case.

See https://dartpad.dev/6f4a65b9734a68c718f6989857f6eb11 a browser-executable version of the code in Dartpad.

