> Hi @Mereep
> I do think the current API reasy to understand: return a error message or return null to indicate that there is not error to show. From what I can see the approach you are suggesting does not get rid of the null value it just makes it implicit.
> 
> This would add just too much complexity into the code base.
> 
> Can you elaborate more what is exactly wrong with the current API and why the one you suggested is better?
> 
> Cc @justinmc

The point is that a function which is called a **validator** should **not** indicate a **success** event using **`return null`** while - in case of failure - return an actual value (only). This totally hides the intent on what is going on and makes the code less readable and also quite akward.

Lets make this clear. We take the example from the cookbook which states

```dart
TextFormField(
  // The validator receives the text that the user has entered.
  validator: (value) {
    if (value.isEmpty) {
      return 'Please enter some text';
    }
    return null;
  },
);
```

which is returning `null` at the end indicating success. If some outsider reads that code, they will not link `return null` to a successful validation. I bet.

Instead, when using the definitions as given above one would write the very same example as:
```dart
TextFormField(
  // The validator receives the text that the user has entered.
  validator: (value) {
    if (value.isEmpty) {
      return Result.Error('Please enter some text'); // Validation is not ok
    }
    return Result.Ok(); // Validation is ok
  },
);
```

which makes the intent of the code totally clear and readable, don't you think?

Edit:

Let me add some benefits:
- this pattern can introduced non-breaking (fall back to `dynamic` as return type, while giving a deprecation warning when the value is not of `Result`). Or even better, give that one https://github.com/dart-lang/language/issues/83 some love. This would even get rid of the deprecation `dynamic`-workaround.
- This pattern is very useful and can be added anywhere an operation may succeed or fail while carrying sound defined information about the reason why that happened. That is:  no wiggling about "Can this function throw? If yes what does it throw? Can the function return `null`? Does it both?" anymore.
- As soons as the types are added a static analyser will hint the user on what to return and not to return for both failure and success.  

Cc @justinmc

